  "summary": "Investigations into the disappearance of Miss Mabel Sainsbury-Sil yield no results, as witnesses at her hotel and in Streatham provide little information and no hospital records match her description. The following morning, Hercule Poirot visits Mr. Howard Rix at the Holborn Palace Hotel. Rix, a disheveled and hungry-looking young man, reacts to Poirot's presence with anger and suspicion.\n\nPoirot reveals that he remembers Rix from the dentist's waiting room three days prior. Rix becomes defensive and accuses Poirot of being a private detective hired by Alistair Brent to protect him. Rix dismisses the investigation, claiming the dentist's death was a suicide caused by a medical error involving a local anesthetic. When Poirot questions Rix regarding his whereabouts between 12:00 and 1:00 PM on the day of the death, Rix remains uncooperative and insists the death is irrelevant to him. Poirot concludes the meeting by noting the contrast between his own concern for the cause of death and Rix's indifference.\n\nUpon returning home, Poirot is met by Miss Gladys Neville, the secretary of the late Mr. Morley. After Poirot offers her tea to calm her nerves, Miss Neville explains that she is upset by the recent trial. She expresses a sense of responsibility for having been present, noting that she felt a woman should have accompanied Miss Morley, especially since Miss Morley disliked Mr. Reilly.",
